{
  "doc_id": "16958",
  "text": "In contrast to motor neuron diseases, MMN is a treatable disorder. It has been reported that patients with MMN improve by treatment with several immunomodulatory agents; however, the best evidence is available for IVIg [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] (Table 3 ). The efficacy of IVIg has been demonstrated in four randomized trials [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Azulay et al. 1994] . Despite clinical improvement observed in all, the data are somewhat conflicting with regard to reversibility of conduction block by IVIg treatment [CITATION_6] ]. GM1 antibody titers do not correlate with treatment response [CITATION_7] , whereas younger patients and those with conduction blocks may benefit more from IVIg treatment. Maintenance therapy is usually required, and if it is stopped, the weakness may progress. Long-term follow-up studies revealed that the effectiveness of IVIg tends to decrease over time [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . In contrast to other chronic immune-mediated neuropathies, corticosteroids and plasma exchange are considered ineffective, and may even worsen the clinical course [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] ].",
